n the rapidly changing social dynamics of the country and region. Analyzing how graffiti makers can reclaim and transform cityscapes that were damaged or monopolized by militias during the war, Sinno explores graffiti’s other roles, including forging civic engagement, commemorating cultural icons, protesting political corruption and environmental violence, and animating resistance. In addition, she argues that graffiti making can offer voices to those who are often marginalized, especially women and LGBTQ people. Copiously illustrated with images of graffiti and street art, A War of Colors is a visually captivating and thought-provoking journey through Beirut, where local and global discourses intersect on both scarred and polished walls in the city.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGraffitixAppreciationzLebanonzBeirut. 0aGraffitixPolitical aspectszLebanonzBeirut. 0aGraffitixSocial aspectszLebanonzBeirut. 0aStreet artxAppreciationzLebanonzBeirut. 0aStreet artxPolitical aspectszLebanonzBeirut. 0aStreet artxSocial aspectszLebanonzBeirut. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aGraffiti, Street Art, Lebanese Visual Culture, Lebanon’s Revolution, Sectarianism, Social Protest in the Arab World, Arab Masculinities, Gender and Sexuality in the Arab World, Postwar Lebanon.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079783140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32874340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477328750423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477328750/original  a978-3-11-079783-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles